\begin_layout Subsection*
Chapter 22:
 Classes,
 Objects,
 and Traits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While Functional Programming handles the logic of transformations,
 Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) handles the 
\series bold
architecture
\series default
 of our data.
 In Scala,
 every value is an object,
 and every operation is a method call.
 This chapter explores how we define these entities and how they collaborate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Classes:
 The Basic Blueprints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A class in Scala is more than just a container for data.
 It defines a type and the behavior associated with it.
 Unlike many other languages,
 Scala 3 allows for a very concise syntax where the constructor is defined right in the class header.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
class Project(val name:
 String,
 var budget:
 Int):
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def increaseBudget(amount:
 Int):
 Unit =
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    budget += amount
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    println(s"New budget for $name is $budget")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    val p = Project("Renaissance",
 1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Case Classes:
 Data Carriers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For most of your domain modeling,
 you will use 
\family typewriter
case classes
\family default
.
 These are specialized classes that automatically provide structural equality (comparing by data,
 not memory address),
 a readable 
\family typewriter
toString
\family default
,
 and the 
\family typewriter
copy
\family default
 method we saw in the functional chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
