// t1 == t2 is true!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Traits:
 The Ultimate Composables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traits are the "Renaissance" version of Interfaces.
 They allow you to define a set of methods that a class must implement,
 but unlike Java interfaces,
 they can also contain fields and implemented logic.
 You "mix" them into classes to build complex behavior from simple parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
trait Searchable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def slug:
 String
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
trait Auditable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def lastModified:
 Long = System.currentTimeMillis()
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
class Document(val title:
 String) extends Searchable with Auditable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def slug = title.toLowerCase.replace(" ",
 "-")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Objects:
 Singletons and Companions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Scala,
 we don't have 
\family typewriter
static
\family default
 members.
 Instead,
 we have the 
\family typewriter
object
\family default
 keyword,
 which defines a 
\series bold
Singleton
\series default
—
a class that has exactly one instance.
 When an object shares the same name as a class,
 it is called a 
\series bold
Companion Object
\series default
.
\end_layout

