\begin_layout Subsection*
Opaque Types vs.
 Classes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we saw in Chapter 19,
 sometimes a class is "too heavy" for a simple ID or wrapper.
 We use 
\family typewriter
opaque type
\family default
 when we want the type safety of a class without the memory overhead of creating an actual object instance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Inheritance and Open Classes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scala 3 encourages composition over inheritance.
 By default,
 classes are "non-open." If you want someone to be able to inherit from your class,
 you must explicitly mark it as 
\family typewriter
open
\family default
.
 This prevents the "Fragile Base Class" problem where changes in a parent class unexpectedly break children.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
open class BaseRenderer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def render():
 Unit = println("Default render")
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
class WebRenderer extends BaseRenderer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  override def render():
 Unit = println("HTML render")
\end_layout

